ce:section.ce:para:
The morphological structure of the scaffolds is characterized by SEM (Fig. 3
                           ). SEM images showed that all scaffolds had a smooth, beadles and randomly oriented fibers with an approximately mean fiber diameter range of 200–400 nm (Table 1
                           ). PCL/PVA-TCP1 had a slightly lower fiber diameter compared to other scaffolds. However, this difference was not significant. In the other words, the addition of TCPs and CDs to the PCL/PVA scaffolds did not alter either the morphology or diameter of the fibers, which can be rooted in the appropriate size distribution of these biomaterials [39,40]. Similar results were reported by Prosecka et al. [39]. These images also indicate that the use of PVA as a water-soluble polymer to dissolve CDs had no effect on the structural morphology of scaffolds. In addition, the fiber diameter of the fabricated scaffolds was similar to the native bone extracellular matrix and previously fabricated PCL-TCP electrospun nanofiber scaffolds in similar articles [41,42].
